76561198315623004,Recommended,225000,24120416,"Posted: 5 July, 2016",all,lowbrowpop,"I am a middle aged woman with a family now, but aside from a few Atari games in the early 80's and Super Mario Bros on Nintendo in the late 80's, Tomb Raider was really the first game that inspired awe in me, in the late 90's. I played all of the games, up to The Last Revelation, before life got in the way and I haven't played any other game since, until now :) Purchasing a new PS4 game console for my 6 YO son and becoming a fan of a lowbrow/pop surreal artist who has done some videogame fanart has inspired me to come back to the world of gaming and happily immerse myself again.Of course, I'm wanting to play many games (and have already purchased over 100 of them on sale - being an adult DOES have it's perks), but I really wanted to start where I left off, which leads me to Chronicles. I have only played for a few hours today, so I'm sure I'll want to update this review at some later date but I just wanted to give a slight review of the game from the perpective of someone with children and responsibilities and as someone who has forgotten many of the talents I garnered in the past...First of all 2 things....If you are person who hasn't played a game in over a decade, like me and you are attempting to turn your computer into a console by purchasing an XBox360 controller, so that you can really pick up where you left off... please understand that  controller support has it's limits. Chronicles purports to offer full controller support, but when I go into options and select ""joystick"" and go back into the game... All Lara does is run around in circles (can't seem to get her to stop) and pull flares! It's okay, I wanted to learn how to game with a keyboard/mouse anyway, but I really didn't want to do that on an adventure game. I just wanted to sit back, relax and enjoy the story without being so clumsy and having to try failed maneuvers over and over again. I've read that controller support is way better in some of the newer version of TR, so I can't wait to try and see.Second, incase you've forgotten! Don't wait until the end of the level for your game to be saved! I made it all the way through level 1 and was about to walk through the Bell Temple door, when I was sent off on another side mission, via a walkthrough, when I missed a jump and lost my life. 15 years ago, this would have been just frustrating, but it would have slid off of my back... but as an adult, with children to feed, a house to keep clean and a business to run... I wanted to cry and vow to never throw away another 4 hrs of my life like that again.The game is just as I remember it (so far) but I just wish I didn't have the ""you could be doing something else"" angel whispering in my ear, because that makes it so much harder to enjoy the game now. But, that's a personal fault(?) and has nothing to do with the game. I would imagine the game makers assumed that users had the time to spare. I still think the graphics are very cool and they do help me to escape a bit, but I've got to be honest, I've seen the graphics on many of the newer games I've purchased, including the newer Tomb Raider titles and I really can't wait to play them."
